# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: batik-cake
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:batik-cake/acar] Through examining the etymology, the similar sounding name strongly suggests that indeed acar was derived from the Indian achar pickle.
[src:batik-cake/acar] Indian achar was transmitted in antiquity to the maritime realm of Southeast Asia, which today is recognized as acar in Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei, and then on to the Philippines as *atchara*.
[src:batik-cake/acar] The adoption of this vegetable pickling technique possibly took place during the Srivijaya period between 7th to 13th century.
[src:batik-cake/acar] British navigator Thomas Forrest wrote that acar made of salted limes and palm vinegar was often of use to Coromandel Muslim sailors (*Chulias*) to prevent scurvy and was sold as far as Aceh.
[src:batik-cake/acar] The Southeast Asian variations are usually made from different vegetables such as cucumber, carrots, cabbage, shallot, bird's eye chili and yardlong beans, which are pickled in vinegar, sometimes with kaffir lime to add citrus aroma, and also dried chillies.
[src:batik-cake/acar] Some recipes might have the vegetables tossed in ground peanuts.
[src:batik-cake/acar] *Acar* is commonly served as a condiment to be eaten with a main course, such as *martabak*, *nasi goreng* (fried rice), satay, and almost all varieties of *soto*.
[src:batik-cake/acar] Just like common pickles, the sour taste of *acar* is meant to freshen up a meal, especially fishy dishes such as *ikan bakar* (grilled fish) or rich and oily dishes such as mutton satay to neutralize the fat.
[src:batik-cake/acar] In Indonesia, acar is commonly made from small chunks of cucumber, carrot, shallot, bird's eye chili and occasionally pineapple, and marinated in a sweet and sour solution of sugar and vinegar.
[src:batik-cake/acar] Some households add lemongrass or ginger to spice it up.
[src:batik-cake/acar] It is usually used as condiment to accompany grilled foods such as satay.
[src:batik-cake/acar] Nevertheless, *acar* can also be consumed as a whole, complete dish.
[src:batik-cake/acar] For example, *ikan acar kuning* is a fish dish (gourami, mackerel or tilapia) served in *acar* pickles of cucumber, carrot, shallot and red chili, mixed with yellow spice paste made of ground turmeric, candlenut, ginger, garlic and shallot.
[src:batik-cake/acar] It is known as *atjar* (pickle) in Dutch cuisine, derived from Indonesian *acar*, since the Netherlands and Indonesia share colonial ties.
[src:batik-cake/acar] Variations of Malaysian and Singaporean *acar* include *acar awak* or Nyonya *acar* and Malay *acar*.
[src:batik-cake/acar] *Acar awak* is more elaborate, containing additional vegetables such as eggplants as well as aromatic spices in the pickling mix.
[src:batik-cake/acar] The salad has also been adopted into Thai cuisine, where it is called *achat* (Thai: อาจาด, pronounced [ʔāː.t͡ɕàːt]).
[src:batik-cake/acar] It is made with cucumber, red chilies, red onions or shallots, vinegar, sugar and salt.
[src:batik-cake/acar] It is served as a side dish with the Thai version of satay (Thai: สะเต๊ะ).
[src:batik-cake/acar] With Indian and Malay slaves initially brought by the British Empire, *atchar* became a favourite condiment in South Africa.
[src:batik-cake/acar] The local variation is usually made with green mangoes.
[src:batik-cake/adhirasam] Adhirasam is a popular as an offering to the relatives during Deepavali and Ganesha Chaturthi festivals, both at home and in temples in Tamil Nadu and Karnataka.
[src:batik-cake/adhirasam] The earliest documented references to Adhirasam emerge from medieval Tamil kingdoms, particularly the Chola dynasty, where it appeared as a favored item in royal feasts and temple rituals.
[src:batik-cake/adhirasam] According to inscriptions from the 16th century, during the reign of Vijayanagara emperor Krishnadevaraya, the sweet was made from rice flour, jaggery, ghee and pepper.
[src:batik-cake/adhirasam] At the annual festival at the Panchavarnesvar Temple in Thirunallur (located near Kumbakonam, Tamil Nadu), an offering of 6000 Adhirasams along with 6000 vadas is made to the Gods; the entire lot is cooked in the temple kitchen between sunrise and 11 pm, for the prayers that take place at midnight.
[src:batik-cake/adhirasam] It is a popular Deepavali sweet preparation for Tamil people.
[src:batik-cake/adhirasam] The authentic preparation takes about a week.
[src:batik-cake/adhirasam] First the rice is soaked in water and dried in shade and ground into a fine powder when the rice is 3/4th dried and retains some moisture.
[src:batik-cake/adhirasam] For adding sweet "vellam" (jaggery in Tamil) is melted in water by boiling it till it reaches soft-ball consistency (235–240 °F (113–116 °C), if using a candy thermometer) and added to the rice flour along with some powdered cardamom to make a thick dough.
[src:batik-cake/adhirasam] It is then transferred to an earthenware pot and the top of the pot is closed with a thin white cloth.
[src:batik-cake/adhirasam] It is then allowed to ferment for about 3–5 days by placing it in the sunlight during the day.
[src:batik-cake/adhirasam] Finally, when the batter is ready for preparation, small balls of the dough is taken and flattened using fingers in a small piece of oil-brushed banana leaf and deep fried in oil until golden brown.
[src:batik-cake/adhirasam] Then it is pressed with a flat bottomed bowl to remove the excess oil.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] Traditionally, an ice shaving machine is used to churn out the shaved ice used in the dessert, originally hand cranked but now more often motorised.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] Many Southeast Asian coffee shops, hawker centres and food courts sell this dessert.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] Early versions of ais kacang was first known to have been prepared around the time before and after the First World War, where the costs of ice manufacturing was becoming more affordable.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] An earlier variant of the Singaporean dish was described as green, made from shaved ice, paired with syrups, *soaked seeds* and seaweed jelly and was sold mainly by street vendors.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] The dish underwent many different alterations and variants throughout the history of Singapore, where during the 1920s, one version of it was described as shaved ice topped with rose water, lime or liquorice.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] A version of the dish, known as Kachang mera, was also sold during the 1930s.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] By the 1940s, the version of the dish described as having "shaved ice heaped into a little mountain", topped with red beans, "a Chinese grape-like fruit", syrup, and condensed or evaporated milk, similar to how it is being prepared today, began to appear.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] Some earlier variants of ais kacang are no longer sold, such as the ice ball version of the dessert, which was popular during the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] In Malaysia, variants now contain a large serving of *attap chee* (palm seed), red beans, sweet corn, grass jelly, roasted peanuts, and cubes of agar agar as common ingredients.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] Other less common ingredients include aloe vera, *cendol*, *nata de coco*, and ice cream.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] A final topping of evaporated milk, condensed milk, or coconut milk is drizzled over the mountain of ice along with red rose syrup and sarsi syrup.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] Some stalls have even introduced novelty toppings such as durian and chocolate syrup.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] There are also versions that shun the multi-coloured syrup and are served instead with just a drizzling of palm sugar syrup.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] In Singapore, traditional ice kachang is usually made from shaved ice, packed into a mountain-like shape and consists of red beans, creamed corn, attap chee, cendol, and grass jelly, similar to the Malaysian version, and drizzled with syrups made from gula melaka, red rose syrup, and pandan syrup.
[src:batik-cake/ais-kacang] The dish has evolved to include fruits such as durian, mango, toppings such as Milo, peanuts, and sago pearls among others.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Based on a report released by International Organisation of Good Templars in 2016, Malaysia has the third highest tax on alcohol worldwide at 15%, behind Norway and Singapore which are predicted to keep increasing.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] The country has an annual spending of RM2 billion on alcoholic drinks.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Prior to the Trans-Pacific Partnership, Malaysia together with Vietnam plans to drop import tariffs on beer, whisky, and other alcoholic drinks.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] The tradition of brewing alcoholic drinks in Malaysia is most prominent in the island of Borneo.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Indigenous islanders traditionally drank home-made rice wine called tuak and tapai in their communal gatherings and harvest festivals of Gawai Dayak and Kaamatan.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Alcohol consumption in the Malay Peninsula has been less common since the introduction of Islam.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] However, the production and consumption of alcohol (*arak*) has been a tradition since the time of Hang Tuah in the 15th century.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] In the 20th century, palm toddy was popular among the local Indian and Chinese communities.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] The British brought their own traditional brewed alcoholic drinks, such as beer and stout.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] In the 1930, the first brewery was established in neighbouring British Singapore.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Since the British colonial times, Tiger Beer was the first commercial beer brewed in 1932 by Malayan Breweries Limited, a Singapore-based brewery which was formed from a merger between Heineken and Fraser and Neave (F&N).
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] The beginning of alcohol production in Malaysia started in 1968, when two leading breweries, Guinness and Malayan, merged to form a new company known as Guinness Anchor Berhad.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] In 1970, Carlsberg established its first brewery outside Kuala Lumpur in Shah Alam.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Both are since the only legal commercial breweries in Malaysia, which account for 95% of the total beer and stout volume in the country market.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] In 2007, another two breweries known as Napex and Jaz brewed beer for pubs in the country, but both have since ceased from operation.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Beside local productions, many alcoholic drinks in the country are also imported from neighbouring countries such as Singapore, Thailand, Indonesia, Philippines and Vietnam.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] The legal drinking age (purchasing) for Malaysia is 21 years old and above.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Since 2020, the legal limit for blood alcohol level while driving in Malaysia is 50 mg per 100 ml for blood test; 22 μg per 100 ml for breath test; and 67 mg per 100 ml for urine test.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Public drinking or public intoxication is not a crime in Malaysia, unless the drunken person caused "annoyance" towards others or exhibit "disorderly behaviour", which may be punished with a RM20 to RM25 fine or a 10 to 14 days jail under the Penal Code or Minor Offences Act 1955.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] However, these laws are rarely enforced.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Any vendors, restaurants and retailers need a licence to serve or sell tap/draft beers, liquor and spirits in the country.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Bottled and canned beers are exempted from such licence requirements, which is why it is common to find many vendors and coffee houses serving alcohol in their premises without a licence.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Malaysia also imposes nationwide regulations for vendors to place their alcoholic drinks into separate refrigerators or storage places, although this was opposed by certain vendors in the state of Penang.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] The high tax on alcohol has increased the price of alcoholic drinks in Malaysia, harming some drinkers who turn to unsafe alcohol smuggled in from neighbouring countries.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] In 2018, around 45 people died in the country's worst methanol poisoning involving foreign workers and several Malaysians due to the consumption of cheap fake liquors acquired from the country's black markets.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Following Demerit Points System for Traffic Offences (KEJARA), a police officer or JPJ officer can take breath, blood or urine samples of drunk driver.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] If alcohol content is found in the samples, a fine of RM 2000 or 6 months' imprisonment may be imposed for the first offence.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Alcohol is generally prohibited for Muslim consumers in the country as Malaysia's sharia law forbids Muslims from drinking alcohol.
[src:batik-cake/alcohol-in-malaysia] Alcohol is mostly banned for Muslims in the states of Kelantan and Terengganu.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Approximately 75% of aluminium foil is used for packaging of foods, cosmetics, and chemical products, and 25% is used for industrial applications (e.g., thermal insulation, electrical cables, and electronics).
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Aluminium foil supplanted tin foil in the mid-20th century.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] In the United Kingdom and United States it is often informally called "tin foil", just as steel cans are often still called "tin cans".
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Metallised films are sometimes mistaken for aluminium foil, but are actually polymer films coated with a thin layer of aluminium.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Foil made from a thin leaf of tin was commercially available before its aluminium counterpart.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Tin foil was marketed commercially from the late nineteenth into the early twentieth century.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] The term "tin foil" survives in the English language as a term for the newer aluminium foil.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Tin foil is less malleable than aluminium foil and tends to give a slight tin taste to food wrapped in it.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Tin foil has been supplanted by aluminium and other materials for wrapping food.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] The first audio recordings on phonograph cylinders were made on tin foil.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Tin was first replaced by aluminium in 1910, when the first aluminium foil rolling plant, Dr.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Lauber, Neher & Cie. was opened in Emmishofen, Switzerland.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Neher & Sons, the aluminium manufacturers, was founded in 1886 in Schaffhausen, Switzerland, at the foot of the Rhine Falls, whose energy powered the process.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] In December 1907, Neher's sons, along with Dr.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Lauber, had invented the endless rolling process, by which they discovered that aluminium foil could be used as a protective barrier.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Bern-based Tobler began wrapping its chocolate bars in aluminium foil in 1911, including the unique triangular chocolate bar, Toblerone.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Aluminium foil has a thickness less than 0.2 mm (7.9 mils); thinner gauges down to 6 μm (0.24 mils) are also commonly used.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Standard household foil is typically 0.016 mm (0.63 mils) thick, and heavy-duty household foil is typically 0.024 mm (0.94 mils).
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Foil may have a non-stick coating on only one side.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Although aluminium is non-magnetic, it is a good conductor, so even a thin sheet reflects almost all of an incident electric wave.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] At frequencies more than 100 MHz, the transmitted electric field is attenuated by more than 80 decibels (dB), that is less than 10−8 = 0.00000001 of the power gets through.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Thin sheets of aluminium are not very effective at attenuating low-frequency magnetic fields.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] The shielding effectiveness is dependent upon the skin depth.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] A field travelling through one skin depth will lose about 63% of its energy (it is attenuated to 1/*e* = 1/2.718... of its original energy).
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Thin shields also have internal reflections that reduce the shielding effectiveness.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] The continuous casting method is much less energy-intensive and has become the preferred process.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] After the rollers, the two sheets are separated, which produces foil with one shiny side and one matte side.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] The two sides in contact with each other are matte, and the exterior sides become shiny.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] The difference in thermal properties between the two sides is imperceptible without instrumentation.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] By Kirchhoff's law of radiation, increased reflectivity decreases both absorption and emission of radiation.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Aluminium foil is available in various types, classified by thickness, alloy composition, manufacturing process, and surface treatment.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] The most common classification is by thickness (or gauge), which determines the foil's strength, flexibility, and application.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Other distinctions are based on temper, surface finish, and intended use.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] The thickness of aluminium foil is typically measured in microns (μm) or mils (thousandths of an inch).
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Aluminium foil is widely sold into the consumer market, such as for wrapping leftovers to be stored in a refrigerator or barbecuing delicate foods.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] As with all metallic items, it reacts to being placed in a microwave oven.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] This is because of the electromagnetic fields of the microwaves inducing electric currents in the foil and high potentials at the sharp points of the foil sheet; if the potential is sufficiently high, it will cause electric arcing to areas with lower potential, even to the air surrounding the sheet.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Modern microwave ovens have been designed to prevent damage to the cavity magnetron tube from microwave energy reflection, and aluminium packages designed for microwave heating are available.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Submerged in a baking soda solution, it can be used to polish metals such as silver and gold via electrolytic cleaning, as it is a more reactive metal than either.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] A similar method can be used to produce silver substrates for Raman spectrography.
[src:batik-cake/aluminium-foil] Some aluminium foil products can be recycled at around 5% of the original energy cost.
[src:batik-cake/amandine-dessert] These cakes are among the most traditional "sweetshop" cakes in Romania.
[src:batik-cake/amandine-dessert] The original recipe has layers of chocolate sponge cake soaked in rum flavored caramel syrup.
[src:batik-cake/amandine-dessert] The cream filling is a combination of chocolate buttercream mixed with fondant.
[src:batik-cake/amandine-dessert] The assembled layers are glazed with a combination of fondant with chocolate and rum or rum essence, poured over the cake while still slightly liquid.
[src:batik-cake/amandine-dessert] These cakes also have a traditional decoration on top with a little bit of the cream and a diamond-shaped piece of thin chocolate.
[src:batik-cake/batik-cake] Batik cake gets its name from the pattern of how the cake is cut out, which resembles the motif of batik clothing when the biscuits are broken and mixed with the chocolate mixture, subsequently forming a unique and irregular alternating abstract pattern when cut.
[src:batik-cake/batik-cake] It is one of the very few Malaysian desserts that does not use any tropical ingredients, similar to hedgehog slice and the latest Prince William chocolate biscuit cake, although with some different ingredients.
[src:batik-cake/batik-cake] In Brunei, the Batik cake is covered by green colour topping.
[src:batik-cake/batik-cake] The cake is made by breaking Marie biscuits into halves or quarters and preparing its chocolate base in a large pot or wok by melting the butter over medium-low heat for 2–3 minutes, followed by the adding of chicken eggs and vanilla extract.
